00:04:29.505 --> 00:04:32.225
So now when we start to talk about special education,

00:04:32.225 --> 00:04:36.225
everybody knows this is one that varies from year to year significantly.

00:04:36.225 --> 00:04:39.505
It's not one that we truly have much control over.

00:04:39.905 --> 00:04:48.170
Special education services aren't optional. And, of course, we wanna provide everything that's needed for our kids. But quite frankly, we really have to look at this,

00:04:48.650 --> 00:04:52.890
from the point of view of the fact that we are legally obligated to.

00:04:53.210 --> 00:04:56.250
So when we look at our, itemized

00:04:56.250 --> 00:04:56.970
potential,

00:04:57.210 --> 00:04:58.170
expenditures

00:04:58.065 --> 00:05:04.465
for next year, that's really not an area that we have much control over. Because of our obligation,

00:05:04.545 --> 00:05:16.140
we don't get to look at those lines and say, perhaps we could eliminate a service, a supply, or a resource at will here. That just isn't one of those that we can do. And all of the services

00:05:16.140 --> 00:05:21.260
that we currently provide are required services. We don't have any extra things,

00:05:21.740 --> 00:05:22.140
like,

00:05:22.860 --> 00:05:26.380
that that are not, something that we use on a daily basis.

00:05:27.495 --> 00:05:30.295
Without giving too much information away of our students,

00:05:30.615 --> 00:05:33.175
I can give you some statistics

00:05:33.175 --> 00:05:36.455
about what our special education looks like here at AES.

00:05:36.855 --> 00:05:40.950
We currently have 25 students who qualify for IEPs,

00:05:41.110 --> 00:05:50.150
and there's three referrals in the process. Doesn't necessarily mean we'll go up to 28. It just means that at any given moment in time, when we look at those numbers,

00:05:50.390 --> 00:05:51.430
we oftentimes

00:05:51.430 --> 00:05:53.750
are looking at what's called a referral,

00:05:55.305 --> 00:05:57.065
which is completely normal,

00:05:57.385 --> 00:05:59.225
in in every school district.

00:05:59.545 --> 00:06:08.665
We have 22 students that have what are called five zero four plans. Now if anybody doesn't know what an IEP is, an IEP is an individualized educational program.

00:06:09.200 --> 00:06:10.480
It means that,

00:06:10.800 --> 00:06:15.200
it was decided by a team that included parents and educators,

00:06:15.200 --> 00:06:15.600
other,

00:06:16.720 --> 00:06:17.920
support services.

00:06:18.400 --> 00:06:23.600
It was decided that there were services that were required for a particular student who had a disability.

00:06:24.085 --> 00:06:25.445
That's an IEP.

00:06:25.765 --> 00:06:29.205
And so once that document, which is a legal binding document,

00:06:29.285 --> 00:06:30.245
is created,

00:06:30.645 --> 00:06:35.925
again, we're required to provide those services. Not that we don't want to. We do, but we are required.

00:06:36.720 --> 00:06:48.480
The difference in a five zero four plan is a five zero four plan, and we do try to cover this every year for those people who don't know, a five zero four plan is also a legal binding document.

00:06:48.720 --> 00:06:50.080
And it has modifications

00:06:50.355 --> 00:06:54.195
and accommodations in it for a student who is in need.

00:06:54.515 --> 00:07:00.195
But it isn't the same because it's not a student that has a particular label of special education.

00:07:02.850 --> 00:07:05.810
It could be a situation that's temporary in nature.

00:07:06.210 --> 00:07:07.490
If a child

00:07:08.290 --> 00:07:12.450
breaks their right arm and they are, right handed when they write,

00:07:13.010 --> 00:07:24.465
we may potentially have to go to 504 and say, how is this person's program going to look different because they can't write for the next six weeks or eight weeks? Or maybe it's a severe situation,

00:07:24.785 --> 00:07:32.960
and, it may be longer than that. So a five zero four plan is, again, a legal binding document that requires services,

00:07:33.360 --> 00:07:38.080
but, it is not necessarily a child that has been labeled special education.

00:07:39.280 --> 00:07:42.960
We have 40 kids that also participate in something called SRBI,

00:07:43.365 --> 00:07:44.805
which is scientifically

00:07:44.805 --> 00:07:46.085
research based

00:07:46.165 --> 00:07:47.045
interventions.

00:07:47.125 --> 00:07:48.965
And what that means is that

00:07:50.645 --> 00:07:55.445
the particular student may be having a little hiccup in their curriculum or instruction.

00:07:56.130 --> 00:08:02.050
Maybe the majority of the class has moved on to something, and they just require a little extra.

00:08:03.170 --> 00:08:03.410
I

00:08:03.970 --> 00:08:05.650
people spend their whole careers

00:08:06.210 --> 00:08:14.635
really investigating SRBI and knowing the ins and outs, so I don't wanna narrow it down to a minute. But in short, I will say that SRBI

00:08:14.635 --> 00:08:17.355
is kinda like a short term

00:08:19.035 --> 00:08:22.395
situation where we give something that's

00:08:23.640 --> 00:08:29.560
usually less than twenty six weeks, where we give something that is extra curriculum and instruction

00:08:29.560 --> 00:08:30.920
at a higher level,

00:08:31.480 --> 00:08:34.920
to a particular student to kinda get them over

00:08:35.160 --> 00:08:36.360
that

00:08:36.615 --> 00:08:40.615
that that hump, to get them over this situation where they're just having a difficulty.

00:08:40.855 --> 00:08:46.855
And, again, I feel terrible trying to, you know, wind up saying what SRBI is in a matter of a minute or two, but,

00:08:47.575 --> 00:08:51.300
those students, and this is the reason why I mentioned that, those students,

00:08:51.620 --> 00:08:52.740
are gonna change

00:08:53.060 --> 00:08:59.140
from, time period to time period. So if I had a list right now of 40 kids participating,

00:08:59.460 --> 00:09:04.820
in twenty six weeks, it could be 15 kids. It could still be 40, but they're different children.

00:09:05.475 --> 00:09:08.515
And so we do have to have staff that address those needs.

00:09:09.395 --> 00:09:13.795
But, again, a caseload could vary from time period to time period,

00:09:14.275 --> 00:09:16.035
and we do have to plan for that.

00:09:17.155 --> 00:09:20.515
So although not all preschool or kindergarten students

00:09:20.900 --> 00:09:28.420
require remediation or intervention, the other thing I feel I need to point out is that it is during preschool and kindergarten

00:09:28.500 --> 00:09:30.020
that we oftentimes

00:09:30.020 --> 00:09:31.780
do more

00:09:32.180 --> 00:09:32.980
screenings,

00:09:33.060 --> 00:09:33.860
observations,

00:09:34.265 --> 00:09:35.465
consultations,

00:09:36.025 --> 00:09:38.745
just simply because they're younger, they're new.

00:09:39.385 --> 00:09:40.105
And

00:09:40.425 --> 00:09:41.465
oftentimes,

00:09:42.345 --> 00:09:47.705
this is what drives us to see, is this a child that might need an intervention?

00:09:48.150 --> 00:09:51.510
Is this a child that may need something more?

00:09:51.830 --> 00:09:55.030
Or is this a child that potentially winds up,

00:09:55.510 --> 00:09:58.630
red flag for potential learning disability?

00:09:58.950 --> 00:10:00.710
So I say that because

00:10:01.845 --> 00:10:04.005
a lot of times people don't understand,

00:10:04.565 --> 00:10:13.765
when we look at kindergarten and we say we had 10 screenings, but we didn't wind up with 10 students that required an IEP or a five zero four. They're like, explain.

00:10:14.325 --> 00:10:16.085
What happens here? Why do you have somebody that

00:10:17.250 --> 00:10:24.850
had that many tests to do? It's because it's it's us doing our job here within the building to make sure that the, identified

00:10:25.410 --> 00:10:26.930
red flags are addressed.

00:10:27.490 --> 00:10:31.810
We also do receive students in our pre k and

00:10:32.395 --> 00:10:36.635
next year, our our our pre school and our pre kindergarten program.

00:10:36.875 --> 00:10:38.235
We do receive

00:10:39.035 --> 00:10:44.555
students through a program called birth to three. Let me close this door one second just so you don't hear the vacuum.

00:10:48.880 --> 00:10:50.160
Birth to three

00:10:50.400 --> 00:10:55.200
is a program where, families might have already sought out,

00:10:56.080 --> 00:10:57.040
some

00:10:57.615 --> 00:10:58.495
services

00:10:58.575 --> 00:11:01.535
for their infant or toddler.

00:11:01.695 --> 00:11:06.575
And the birth to three program then will make recommendations

00:11:06.575 --> 00:11:10.495
to the school when the child comes in at three years old.

00:11:11.610 --> 00:11:15.530
And we then would implement them and continue

00:11:15.770 --> 00:11:18.570
with monitoring and servicing the child,

00:11:19.050 --> 00:11:21.370
from birth to three on through.

00:11:21.690 --> 00:11:30.865
Early intervention, we've always said is vital, and I think one of the best things Andover did was to, make sure that we had the capacity to address our kids earlier.

00:11:32.065 --> 00:11:34.785
So what types of services do we provide?

00:11:35.265 --> 00:11:44.590
I think this is important for people who either don't have school aged children or have never had a child in their home in need of services.

00:11:45.470 --> 00:11:47.550
General academic services

00:11:47.550 --> 00:11:52.715
to meet the goals with a regular special education teacher, a regular teacher,

00:11:53.755 --> 00:11:54.555
math,

00:11:54.715 --> 00:11:57.035
reading, any sorts of those things.

00:11:58.235 --> 00:12:02.635
So sorry for the interruption. At least we know the custodian's working on cleaning the wrong ones.

00:12:03.835 --> 00:12:04.235
Sorry.

00:12:05.810 --> 00:12:07.170
We require,

00:12:07.570 --> 00:12:14.370
in some cases, social work services. And so we definitely have to provide those to our our students here.

00:12:14.690 --> 00:12:16.770
We have occupational therapy,

00:12:16.850 --> 00:12:19.810
which we call it OT. That's what occupational therapy is.

00:12:20.475 --> 00:12:21.675
Physical therapy,

00:12:22.475 --> 00:12:24.235
we provide psychological

00:12:24.235 --> 00:12:25.595
services and testing.

00:12:25.995 --> 00:12:30.555
We provide speech and language, and SLP is a speech and language professional.

00:12:31.435 --> 00:12:32.555
Paraprofessional

00:12:32.555 --> 00:12:34.395
assistance to students who need that.

00:12:35.590 --> 00:12:38.710
Busing would fall under here because very oftentimes,

00:12:38.950 --> 00:12:45.670
that is part of a program for a child. And it could be through an IEP, and it could be through the five zero four process.

00:12:46.390 --> 00:12:46.950
Either way,

00:12:47.635 --> 00:12:52.115
busing is often something that falls under the umbrella of special education services,

00:12:52.275 --> 00:12:55.395
whether it's to another facility or to our own.

00:12:56.915 --> 00:12:59.715
Outplacement services when they are necessary.

00:13:01.280 --> 00:13:02.160
Adaptive

00:13:02.160 --> 00:13:03.200
technology,

00:13:03.600 --> 00:13:08.000
which means that sometimes there are students that need specialized things, specialized,

00:13:08.320 --> 00:13:11.680
pencils, specialized computers, specialized desks,

00:13:12.320 --> 00:13:14.240
anything where we have to adapt

00:13:15.045 --> 00:13:18.725
the technology that we currently use with our traditional students.

00:13:20.005 --> 00:13:25.525
And I put nursing services on here. We won't be looking at the nurses specifically

00:13:25.525 --> 00:13:36.460
until we get to the the salary section, but, we do have certain students within the building that require things of our nurse that other students do not.

00:13:36.860 --> 00:13:37.820
And therefore,

00:13:37.900 --> 00:13:40.060
that would be, a special education service.

00:13:42.075 --> 00:13:46.315
So when we look at, you know, how do you figure out, Valerie, year,

00:13:47.435 --> 00:13:55.515
exactly if you have the right mix of hours for these professionals. Like, how do you know if you need a full time person, a part time person,

00:13:56.250 --> 00:13:57.930
somebody that you hire out?

00:13:58.650 --> 00:14:00.890
We look at those IEPs.

00:14:00.970 --> 00:14:03.130
We look at the five o fours.

00:14:03.450 --> 00:14:08.810
We look at who the students are that are currently being serviced by our professionals,

00:14:09.210 --> 00:14:10.250
and we say,

00:14:10.570 --> 00:14:16.465
will next year bring about the same thing? Will it bring about more hours, less hours,

00:14:16.545 --> 00:14:17.985
a different professional,

00:14:17.985 --> 00:14:19.745
kind of where we are with this?

00:14:20.465 --> 00:14:21.345
Currently,

00:14:21.425 --> 00:14:26.545
if I look at our legally binding documents, our 504s and our IEPs,

00:14:27.040 --> 00:14:36.880
I know that there's a total per week of eighty one point five academic hours where they need to work with somebody other than the classroom teacher.

00:14:38.080 --> 00:14:44.165
We know that there are twenty three point five hours right now, anticipated for next year

00:14:44.165 --> 00:14:47.125
where they need to work with a speech and language provider,

00:14:48.325 --> 00:14:52.645
twelve hours where they need to work directly with the psychologist,

00:14:53.010 --> 00:14:55.410
six point five for a social worker,

00:14:55.970 --> 00:14:58.850
eight hours for an occupational therapist,

00:14:59.250 --> 00:15:02.130
and four hours for a physical therapist.

00:15:02.370 --> 00:15:03.090
Now

00:15:03.570 --> 00:15:05.250
I put this slide first.

00:15:05.970 --> 00:15:14.935
These are the direct service hours. And no matter what field you're in, you all know that there are the hours where you actually do your job,

00:15:15.255 --> 00:15:19.815
and then there are the hours that you have to do all of the other things that are associated with your job.

00:15:20.540 --> 00:15:23.020
And for these service providers,

00:15:23.100 --> 00:15:25.820
what does that look like? They look like this.

00:15:27.260 --> 00:15:32.060
In addition to the time when they are physically one on one with the child

00:15:32.455 --> 00:15:38.535
or two on one, whatever, it is that that they have, on the, binding document.

00:15:38.935 --> 00:15:41.575
These are the other things that those providers

00:15:41.655 --> 00:15:45.015
need to do to prepare to service the children.

00:15:45.690 --> 00:15:50.970
They have to attend those meetings, the PPT meetings, the planning and placement team meetings.

00:15:51.690 --> 00:15:58.490
And on a particular student, there could be one a year. There could be multiple a year. There could be eight a year depending

00:15:58.490 --> 00:15:58.730
on

00:15:59.295 --> 00:16:01.855
whether or not it's it's a new student here,

00:16:02.175 --> 00:16:05.775
depending on if changes need to be made to accommodate

00:16:05.775 --> 00:16:07.055
those students.

00:16:07.615 --> 00:16:08.575
Screenings,

00:16:09.375 --> 00:16:10.255
evaluations

00:16:10.255 --> 00:16:11.295
and testing,

00:16:11.615 --> 00:16:13.535
written documentation and reports,

00:16:14.270 --> 00:16:17.070
classroom observations and communications

00:16:17.070 --> 00:16:20.350
to parents or to other service providers,

00:16:20.910 --> 00:16:22.430
other responsibilities,

00:16:22.670 --> 00:16:27.310
and then things like to train classroom staff on implementation.

00:16:27.310 --> 00:16:34.335
So if there is a particular method that they are utilizing to address a student, an accommodation or a modification,

00:16:34.415 --> 00:16:42.575
they need to make sure when they aren't there with the child that everybody else that comes in contact with them knows exactly what the game plan is.

00:16:43.190 --> 00:16:46.230
And that if there's adaptive technology, for example,

00:16:46.550 --> 00:16:49.990
that they know how to utilize the adaptive technology.

00:16:50.390 --> 00:16:52.870
And so all of these other hours,

00:16:53.590 --> 00:16:59.085
they can vary from student to student depending on the needs, but all of these other things are worked into

00:16:59.245 --> 00:17:01.245
and in addition to these hours.

00:17:02.125 --> 00:17:02.765
